# Creating an ontology for the domain of IoT testbeds involves defining classes, properties, and relationships while reusing existing ontologies where applicable. Below is a Turtle (RDF) representation of an IoT testbed ontology that incorporates elements from the Fiesta-IoT ontology and other relevant vocabularies.

# ```turtle
@prefix : <http://example.org/iot-testbed#> .
@prefix fi: <http://fiesta-iot.eu/ontology#> .
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix foaf: <http://xmlns.com/foaf/0.1/> .

# Ontology Declaration
<http://example.org/iot-testbed>
    rdf:type owl:Ontology ;
    rdfs:label "IoT Testbed Ontology" ;
    rdfs:comment "An ontology for representing IoT testbeds, their components, and interactions." .

# Classes
:IoTTestbed rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "IoT Testbed" ;
    rdfs:comment "A testbed for Internet of Things devices and applications." .

:Device rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Device" ;
    rdfs:comment "A physical or virtual device in the IoT testbed." .

:Sensor rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :Device ;
    rdfs:label "Sensor" ;
    rdfs:comment "A device that senses physical properties." .

:Actuator rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf :Device ;
    rdfs:label "Actuator" ;
    rdfs:comment "A device that acts upon the environment." .

:Network rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Network" ;
    rdfs:comment "The communication network connecting devices in the testbed." .

:Experiment rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Experiment" ;
    rdfs:comment "An experiment conducted within the IoT testbed." .

:Data rdf:type rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label "Data" ;
    rdfs:comment "Data generated or used by devices in the testbed." .

# Object Properties
:hasDevice rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has device" ;
    rdfs:domain :IoTTestbed ;
    rdfs:range :Device ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an IoT testbed to its devices." .

:hasNetwork rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has network" ;
    rdfs:domain :IoTTestbed ;
    rdfs:range :Network ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an IoT testbed to its network." .

:conductsExperiment rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "conducts experiment" ;
    rdfs:domain :IoTTestbed ;
    rdfs:range :Experiment ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an IoT testbed to the experiments conducted." .

:generatesData rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "generates data" ;
    rdfs:domain :Device ;
    rdfs:range :Data ;
    rdfs:comment "Links a device to the data it generates." .

:uses rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
    rdfs:label "uses" ;
    rdfs:domain :Experiment ;
    rdfs:range :Device ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an experiment to the devices it uses." .

# Data Properties
:hasName rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has name" ;
    rdfs:domain :Device ;
    rdfs:range xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "The name of the device." .

:hasType rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has type" ;
    rdfs:domain :Device ;
    rdfs:range xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "The type of the device (e.g., sensor, actuator)." .

:hasValue rdf:type owl:DatatypeProperty ;
    rdfs:label "has value" ;
    rdfs:domain :Data ;
    rdfs:range xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "The value of the data generated." .

# Example Instances
:Testbed1 rdf:type :IoTTestbed ;
    :hasDevice :Sensor1, :Actuator1 ;
    :hasNetwork :Network1 ;
    :conductsExperiment :Experiment1 .

:Sensor1 rdf:type :Sensor ;
    :hasName "Temperature Sensor" ;
    :hasType "Temperature" .

:Actuator1 rdf:type :Actuator ;
    :hasName "Fan" ;
    :hasType "Cooling" .

:Network1 rdf:type :Network ;
    :hasName "WiFi Network" .

:Experiment1 rdf:type :Experiment ;
    :uses :Sensor1, :Actuator1 .

:Data1 rdf:type :Data ;
    :hasValue "22.5" .

# ```

# ### Explanation:
# 1. **Classes**: The ontology defines several classes relevant to IoT testbeds, including `IoTTestbed`, `Device`, `Sensor`, `Actuator`, `Network`, `Experiment`, and `Data`.
# 2. **Object Properties**: Relationships between classes are established through object properties such as `hasDevice`, `hasNetwork`, `conductsExperiment`, `generatesData`, and `uses`.
# 3. **Data Properties**: Attributes of devices and data are captured through data properties like `hasName`, `hasType`, and `hasValue`.
# 4. **Instances**: Example instances illustrate how the classes and properties can be instantiated in a real-world scenario.

# This ontology can be expanded further based on specific requirements or additional features of IoT testbeds.